To connect to your personal github account, you need to do so over SSH. Using classical tokens, or fine-grained tokens could cause potential balding.

-1 ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "email-registered-with-github"
You're going to be prompted to give the file a name to save the generated ssh key, you can using the default by just using ```Enter``` button

-2 After that run these series of commnads:
    ```bash
    cd ~/.ssh; ls
    ```
    You should see the the name of the file that the generated key was saved to and a ```.pub``` file with the same name
    ```bash
    known_hosts saved-file saved-file.pub
    ```

    Copy the contents of the .pub file as it contains the public key file 
    ```bash
    cat saved-file.pub | pbcopy
    ```
    Now you have the contents of the file in your clipboard


-3 Open your github account, and go to: ```Settings->SSH and GPG Keys```. And click on ```Add new ssh key```
   Hit ```Cmd + V``` and continue. Now github knows that whenever we connect, it can authenticate us based on the provided key 


-4  In your terminal, run the follwing commands:
    ```bash
    cd ~/.ssh
    touch config
    vim config
    ```

    And then paste the following:
      Host github.com-your-user-name
        HostName ssh.github.com 
        User git 
        IdentityFile ~/.ssh/saved-file

-5 And then for your repository, you'll need to change the protocol to use ssh instead of HTTPS
  ```bash
  git remote set-url origin git@github.com-<username>:<username>/repo.git
  ```
  Now any operations done on this repository will be over SSH

-6 The last step is to test the connection
  ```bash 
  ssh -vvvT git@github.com-username
  ```
  You will be prompted to keep the connection with github, and enter yes
  This just prints out processes to the terminal for debugging clues such as dropped packets or errors, but regardless, you sould see:
  "Hi username! You have been successfully authenticated"
